[[File:Enakomachi, Takayama, Gifu Prefecture 506-0818, Japan - panoramio (24).jpg|thumb|250px|Kō Shrine]]

'''Kō Shrine''' (こうじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|qid=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in Enako-chō, {{ill|lt=Takayama|Q622594|qid=Q622594|1=Takayama, Gifu}}, {{ill|lt=Gifu Prefecture|Q131277|qid=Q131277|1=Gifu Prefecture}}. It is also called “Aragami-sha” or “Ara-jinja.”

It is a candidate shrine for Ena Shrine, a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|qid=Q134917286}} of {{ill|lt=Ōno District|Q31671|qid=Q31671|1=Ōno District, Gifu}}, {{ill|lt=Hida Province|Q1056535|qid=Q1056535|1=Hida Province}}. The Shikinaisha Ena Shrine is usually taken as {{ill|lt=Ena Shrine|Q11618316|qid=Q11618316|1=Ena Shrine}} in the same Enako-chō, Takayama, but this identification was made in {{ill|lt=Bunka era|Q1373146|qid=Q1373146|lt=Bunka|1=Bunka}} 12 ({{ill|lt=1815|Q6948|qid=Q6948|1=1815}}) by the Takayama kokugaku scholar {{ill|lt=Tanaka Ōhidesu|Q6536652|qid=Q6536652|1=Tanaka Ōhide}}, who identified Koyasu Daimyōjin in Inaki no Mori, Enako-chō, as the Shikinaisha Ena Shrine because “Ena” was interpreted as {{ill|lt=placenta|Q1212935|qid=Q1212935|lt=胞衣|1=Placenta}}. Even now, the theory that Kō Shrine is Ena remains strong.

It is located upstream on the Enako River, a tributary of the {{ill|lt=Miya River|Q1156518|qid=Q1156518|lt=Miya River|1=Jinzū River}} in the Jinzu system. There is a theory that the place name Enako changed from Ena.

The founding period is unknown, but it is said to have once been a sacred place where women were prohibited.

=== Enshrined deities ===
*Hi-musubi-no-kami
*{{ill|lt=Kagutsuchi|Q1640658|qid=Q1640658|lt=Hi-no-Yagihayao-no-Kami|1=Kagu-tsuchi}}
*Okutsu-hiko-no-Kami
*Okutsu-hime-no-Kami

=== Annual festival ===
*A festival held once every four years (around Saturday/Sunday near January 7 in leap years). Also called the amazake festival.
*Originally on lunar leap-year November 18, but after Meiji and the solar calendar it changed to leap-year January 7. The current schedule dates from after WWII.
*{{ill|lt=Amazake|Q455990|qid=Q455990|1=Amazake}} and gogoku mochi (rice, barley, soybeans, chestnuts, azuki beans) are served to worshippers.
*Formerly, a {{ill|lt=shimenawa|Q1887421|qid=Q1887421|1=Shimenawa}} was hung in a rice field, rice was cooked over a fire, amazake was prepared there and left overnight in the field to keep warm, and the quality next morning was used to divine that year’s harvest. Today amazake is prepared in front of Kami-Enako Community Hall.

=== Cultural properties ===
*Meoto cedar trees of Kō Shrine (city-designated natural monument)<ref>{{Cite web|和書|date= |url=http://www.city.takayama.lg.jp/bunkazai/bunkazai/tennnennkinennbutu/data/kojinjyameotosugi.htm |title=荒神社の夫婦スギ |publisher=Takayama City |accessdate=2013-04-21}}</ref>

=== Access ===
*About 5 km southeast from {{ill|lt=Takayama Station|Q874020|qid=Q874020|1=Takayama Station}} on the {{ill|lt=Takayama Main Line|Q1188357|qid=Q1188357|1=Takayama Main Line}}.
**About 1 km north of Hida Furusato Tunnel.

